<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Journal Reporters Win
   Farm-Journalism Prizes
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   DJ
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Two reporters for The Wall Street Journal were
named winners in the 1989 writing contest of the National
Association of Agricultural Journalists.
   Scott Kilman, who covers commodities markets and
agriculture in the Journal's Chicago bureau, received first
prize in the special-projects category for a series of
stories on the spread of aflatoxin, a cancer-causing agent,
in the nation's corn crop.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Kilman, 30 years old, joined The Wall Street Journal
in 1984 and transferred to Chicago from Atlanta in 1986.
   Bruce Ingersoll, who covers agriculture in the Journal's
Washington bureau, was named third-place winner in the
special-projects category for a series of stories on food
safety, including meat inspection deficiencies, illegal
trafficking in unsafe shellfish, and tainted milk.
   Mr. Ingersoll, 48, joined the Journal's Washington bureau
in 1984.
