<HL>
   Merger Activity Fell 13%
   In 1st Quarter From 1989
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   SCHAUMBURG, Ill. -- Cautious buyers and a troubled
junk-bond market continued to depress merger activity in the
first quarter.
   Mergers and acquisitions announced in the first quarter
were down 13% to 597 from 685 a year earlier, according to
W.T. Grimm &amp; Co., a unit of New York-based Merrill Lynch &amp;
Co.'s Merrill Lynch Business Brokerage &amp; Valuation
subsidiary. The total value of transactions plummeted 38% to
$34.3 billion from $55 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The absence of megadeals greatly contributed to the sharp
drop in value, said Beth Rosencrans, research director of the
Merrill Lynch unit. The total value of the 10 largest deals
announced in the latest first quarter was $15.7 billion --
less than the $16.1 billion acquisition, announced last
April, of SmithKline Beckman Corp. by Beecham Group PLC. The
largest transaction announced in the 1990 first quarter was
the $4.4 billion bid for UAL Corp.
   The drop continued a downward trend that began late last
year, Ms. Rosencrans added. In the 1989 fourth quarter, the
number of deals fell 13% while the total value fell 11% from
a year earlier.
   The number of foreign concerns bidding for U.S. companies
rose 31% to 93 from 71 last year. Simultaneously, the dollar
value of those transactions climbed 65% to $12.9 billion from
$7.8 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900424-0122
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900424-0122.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Shooting Down Bison
   Is Anything but a `Hunt'
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A19
</SO>
<LP>
   In regard to Ruth Rudner's April 3 Leisure &amp; Arts article
"Where the Buffalo Don't Roam": Permitting the shooting of
bison that wander outside the boundaries of Yellowstone Park
makes no more sense than declaring open season on animals
that escape from their cages at the zoo. Park officials'
claim of "keeping animals wild by allowing them natural
movement through their natural habitat" is ludicrous. Are
bears that live off garbage and wander up to tourists' cars
begging handouts natural? Yes, "population control has to
happen," but surely it can be accomplished more humanely.
   I saw scenes of the "hunt" on TV -- animal-rights
activists pleading to have a bleeding, struggling animal put
out of its misery while "hunters" stood about laughing,
prolonging the creature's terrible suffering because they got
a kick out of the effect it had on the activists. Even the
park rangers, condoning this behavior and chasing away those
who attempt to keep the animals within park boundaries, don't
behave like real rangers in Yellowstone.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Christine Dale
   Nanuet, N.Y.
   ---
   While Ms. Rudner's article did a fairly accurate job of
portraying a complex situation, attention should be brought
to a coloring of an important fact. Ms. Rudner states,
"Because {bison} can carry brucellosis, which causes cattle
to abort if they come into contact with the fresh afterbirth
of an aborted bison fetus, ranchers are understandably
concerned if bison cross the boundary."
   That sounds like reasonable justification for the hunt --
but the Humane Society says there isn't a case on record of
brucellosis being passed from wild bison to domestic cows.
The ranchers' stated reason for protection is actually
nothing more than a smoke screen to masquerade their true
motives -- to eliminate competition from increasingly scarce
grazing lands.
   It's time the public took notice of this travesty, and let
Congress know that it won't put up with the senseless
slaughter of an American treasure.
   Steven E. Rovner
   Jersey City, N.J.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900424-0121
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900424-0121.
</DOCID>
