<HL>
   Coca-Cola Sets Invasion of East Germany,
   Plans $140 Million in Investments There
   ----
   By Glenn Ruffenach
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   KO EUROP PEP
</CO>
<IN>
BEVERAGES (BVG)
</IN>
<LP>
   ATLANTA -- Coca-Cola Co., hoping to match its huge success
in West Germany, is starting a push into East Germany with
$140 million in capital investments.
   The soft-drink giant said negotiations are under way with
beverage organizations in East Germany to bottle and
distribute Coca-Cola throughout the country. The $140 million
would be used to upgrade machinery, trucks, vending machines
and other sales equipment connected with as many as six
bottling plants.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A Coca-Cola spokesman said negotiations are expected to be
completed before the summer.
   East Germany could represent a significant addition to
Coke's highly profitable overseas operations. International
sales today account for 80% of the company's soft-drink
operating profit and 65% of soft-drink revenue. West Germany
alone accounts for about 12% of Coke's earnings, said Emanuel
Goldman, an analyst with PaineWebber Research in San
Francisco.
   By contrast, Coke's domestic sales have been lackluster.
While the company's international volume grew by 9% in the
first quarter, retail case sales in the U.S. increased 3%,
with fountain volume rising a slim 1%.
   Coke first moved to take advantage of the East German
market last fall when the Berlin Wall began to crumble,
offering free soft drinks to people crossing the border.
Since mid-February, Coke has sold more than two million cases
of soft drinks in East Germany, shipped into the country from
bottling plants in West Germany and France. By comparison,
the company sold about four million cases in Poland in all of
1989.
   The fact that Coke is already a known commodity in East
Germany -- its West German television ads have been seen by
East German viewers for 30 years-and the existence of
bottling facilities in the country mean that Coke should be
able to break into the market more easily and more quickly
than it would normally in a foreign country.
   "The demand is there, and the awareness is there," said a
Coke spokesman. "But up until now, there's just been an
inability to buy the product."
   Added Mr. Goldman at PaineWebber: "The key is
availability. If there's one thing Coca-Cola has shown it can
do, it's making the product available and affordable. If they
can meld the two operations (in East and West Germany),
there's a potential for substantial profits."
   The company's move into East Germany comes on the heels of
PepsiCo Inc.'s new trade agreement with the Soviet Union. The
Purchase, N.Y., company plans to spend more than $1 billion
to upgrade and expand bottling plants and to provide
concentrate, among other things. The accord could double
Pepsi's sales in the Soviet Union during the next 10 years.
The company sold about 40 million cases there in 1989. Coke
sold about 20 million cases of all its products, including
Fanta orange drink, in the Soviet Union.
   While Pepsi claims to have a substantial lead over Coke in
most of Eastern Europe, Pepsi acknowledges that East Germany
is the one country in the bloc where Coke is dominant. A
Pepsi spokesman said yesterday, however, that the company is
"aggressively pursuing" franchise operations in East Germany
and expects to reach agreements with some East German
bottlers in the "next few weeks." The spokesman declined to
elaborate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900424-0101
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900424-0101.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   A Trade Deficit Primer
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<LP>
   As an April 30 deadline looms, the tom-toms of trade war
are once again beating at George Bush to take a "Super 301"
swipe at Japan, and maybe South Korea too. It's time to
repeat that the conventional wisdom on trade deficits has it
all exactly backward.
   The U.S. does not have a trade deficit with Japan because
this country consumes too much and must therefore borrow to
pay the bill. The trade deficit exists because Japan has to
find somewhere to invest its huge pool of savings. The United
States, which happens to be a very good place to invest, then
buys Toyotas to recycle those savings back to Japan through
the trade account. In other words, the trade deficit is a
sign of American economic vigor, not weakness.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   We know this may sound startling, because the conventional
wisdom has deemed that somehow there is a perfect trade
"balance," presumably at or close to zero. This logic ignores
the central truth of foreign trade flows: There can't be a
trade deficit without offsetting capital inflows. The trade
deficit or surplus is merely an accounting identity.
   To refresh some memories on this point, it's worth
reprinting the 1976 conclusions of the U.S. Advisory
Committee on the Presentation of Balance of Payments
Statistics. This was not a group of economic yahoos, but
included Morgan Guaranty's Rimmer de Vries, Brookings's
Walter Salant and Charles Schwartz of the International
Monetary Fund. The committee said:
   "The words `surplus' and `deficit' should be avoided
insofar as possible. . . . These words are frequently taken
to mean that the developments are `good' or `bad'
respectively. Since that interpretation is often incorrect,
the terms may be widely misunderstood and used in lieu of
analysis."
   So long as foreign investment here is voluntary and
private, a trade deficit is a motor of growth and prosperity.
If it's a trade surplus we want, there's one quick way to get
it: recession. To put it another way, in today's global
economy, investment or capital flows drive trade flows,
rather than vice versa. A mere two weeks of capital flows add
up to more than a year's worth of trade flows. Trade is the
result not the cause.
   With that in mind, it's hard to understand why the U.S. as
the world's leading economic power should pick trade fights
with Japan or anyone else. With Japan's trade surplus, its
high (and for years subsidized) savings rate and anemic
consumption, where else but the U.S. can Japan's money go? If
Japan's dollars weren't somehow recycled, we'd all be in a
fix that would take the "trade deficit" right out of the
economic news.
   So what's driving U.S. trade policy? Clear as day:
politics, especially lobbying by U.S. producer interests. The
201 and Super 301 trade-retaliation sections of the 1988
trade bill are engraved invitations for special corporate
pleading. Indeed, they were expressly designed by Congress to
make Congress and the interests it represents bigger players
in trade policy.
   One year into the law, industry has already formed a
protectionist queue at the 301 table. Last year it was wood
products, satellites and supercomputers. This year, the
foremost agitators are auto parts and computer chips. The
Semiconductor Industry Association, in effect a lobby for
only two companies, has sent a letter urging a 301 case to
virtually the entire Bush Cabinet.
   We have no problem with diplomacy to open markets or
remove Japan's ridiculous trade barriers. Japanese consumers
are themselves agitating for lower prices and better goods,
and the American voice is a useful echo. But in modern trade
politics, no Tokyo concession ever seems to be enough.
Despite recent Japanese concessions in satellites and
computers, Senators John Danforth (R., Mo.) and Max Baucus
(D., Mont.) want George Bush to hit 'em again. Presumably,
the Senators' logic is that one good turn deserves only
another rebuke.
   It may be, of course, that America's trade warriors really
don't understand what they're asking Japan to do. The reforms
they're seeking would actually make Japan's economy more
efficient, and more competitive too. If Japan changes its
retail-store law to allow American-style supermarkets, for
example, Japanese will pay less of their income for food.
Their savings will then increase, creating an even larger
capital outflow and thus a larger U.S. trade deficit.
   This is fine with those of us who think the trade deficit
is really nothing to worry about. In fact, if our trade
warriors are now admitting they agree, we're happy to welcome
them aboard.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900424-0100
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900424-0100.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   At Walden Pond,
   Two Liberal Causes
   Seem One Too Many
   ---
   Rock Star Defends the Site
   From Condos but It Turns
   Out the Poor Need Them
   ----
   By Lawrence Ingrassia
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
HEAVY CONSTRUCTION; INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL (CON)
HOME CONSTRUCTION (HOM)
</IN>
<LP>
   "If I knew for a certainty that a man was coming to my
house with the conscious design of doing me good, I should
run for my life. . . . I never heard of a philanthropic
meeting in which it was sincerely proposed to do any good to
me, or the like of me."
   -- from "Walden"
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   CONCORD, Mass. -- Henry David Thoreau, brace yourself. The
philanthropists are coming.
   Rock star Don Henley is leading the charge, bringing with
him actors Don Johnson and Carrie Fisher and singers Bonnie
Raitt, Arlo Guthrie and Bob Seger. Their mission is to save
Walden Pond from developers, to keep it free from the blot of
civilization.
   They will do this in the way they know best, by charging
locals $22 a ticket to hear them talk about the Pond and sing
some classic rock 'n' roll. Two concerts are planned --
tonight and tomorrow night -- and it's all for a good cause.
   Or is it?
   Mr. Henley -- formerly of the Eagles (hit song: "Hotel
California") and the host of the party where Gary Hart met
Donna Rice -- thought he was going to save Walden Pond from
an office building and condominiums. But it turns out that
the condo project includes some affordable housing -- of
which there is precious little in this exclusive community.
   Suddenly, solid liberal ground became a little shaky. One
state official, implying that Mr. Henley had been hoodwinked,
wrote him a letter cautioning that "the environmental
objections being raised . . . are a thinly veiled attempt" by
hoity-toity Concordians to keep out hoi polloi.
   Besides, others chime in, Walden isn't exactly the
pristine retreat it was when Henry David (as the
philosopher/naturalist is called here) was trekking around
the woods in the 19th century. The office building, proposed
by developer and magazine publisher Mortimer Zuckerman,
wouldn't really mar the scenic shores of Walden. The site is
separated from the pond by a heavily traveled four-lane
highway, the town dump and a trailer park.
   More than a few locals think it's a bit ironic that
jet-setting stars are claiming kinship with the frugal Mr.
Thoreau. But, Mr. Henley told a Boston newspaper, "Thoreau
and Emerson had a great deal of influence in my life. They
made me more aware of nature and the environment." He noted
that he read "Walden" while studying English at North Texas
State University about 20 years ago.
   In a letter to the state, he wrote: "Pieces of our
heritage disappear one by one without people even noticing.
It always comes down to Nature vs. Economics. Nature vs.
Jobs. Nature vs. Profit. Nature vs. this thing we call
`progress' -- and Nature always loses."
   When Mr. Henley found out about the proposed developments,
he offered help to Thomas Blanding, a Thoreau scholar and
president of the Thoreau Country Conservation Alliance.
   No one really doubts the rock star's sincerity. He just
happens to have stepped into a battle that's been going on
for several years, with Mr. Blanding's forces on one side and
the development and housing forces on the other.
   The debate in part reflects Concord's own schizophrenia.
It is trying to maintain its rich past: It was at the Old
North Bridge in Concord on April 19, 1775, that the British
were turned back by the Minutemen. Ralph Waldo Emerson, Mr.
Thoreau's mentor, lived here. So did Nathaniel Hawthorne and
Louisa May Alcott.
   But it is also trying to maintain its rich present: In
recent years Concord has become an expensive suburb, a home
for wealthy Boston commuters. Mr. Thoreau built his humble
one-room home on Walden Pond for $28.12 1/2 cents. Today,
Concord homes cost an average of $300,000; some fetch more
than $1 million.
   Streets are lined with fashionable shops and real-estate
agencies. The entrees at Walden Station Restaurant include
Chicken Thoreau -- "excellent mesquite flavored boneless
breast, with shiitake mushrooms and a boursin cream sauce" --
a dish Mr. Thoreau never mentions cooking on his wood stove
at Walden Pond.
   The pond -- actually more the size of a lake -- lies a
mile-and-a-half south of the town center. Here, Mr. Thoreau
lived a life of contemplation from July 1845 to September
1847. It was an almost idyllic spot, judging by but one
description in his book: "This small lake was of most value
as a neighbor in the intervals of a gentle rainstorm in
August, when, both air and water being perfectly still, but
the sky overcast, mid-afternoon had all the serenity of
evening, and the wood thrush sang around, and was heard from
shore to shore."
   The pond is still beautiful, its water clear and smooth as
glass on a windless day. And, with 411 acres surrounding the
pond given to the state by the Emerson family and others in
1922, the immediate area hasn't been developed.
   But if a wood thrush sings nowadays, you can't hear it,
much less from the other shore.
   At one end of the pond is a man-made beach that draws
thousands of swimmers on hot summer weekends. Anglers line
the shore hoping to catch the trout that's stocked in the
pond by the state. A concrete boat launch sits at one corner
(though only canoes and rowboats are allowed). Constant
traffic on nearby roads creates incessant noise.
   The undulating hills in the surrounding area, where Mr.
Thoreau walked and meditated, are still wooded and, in
places, relatively tranquil. Here -- well out of sight of the
pond -- the new condominiums are planned.
   While Thoreauvians concede that the woods are already
dotted with high-priced homes, they argue that the condos and
office building, though at two separate sites, take
development one step too far. "It's a domino effect. They
talk about the dump across the road," says Ann Chapman, a
Thoreauvian. "If you put this {office building} in, it would
justify another development. What's enough?"
   Planning officials defend the projects. The condos would
be about three-fourths of a mile away from Walden Pond, not
on its shores, notes Judith Chanoux Cutler, Concord's town
planner. Also, the 139-unit condo project, a venture between
two Boston developers, would include 42 units of low- or
moderate-income housing subsidized by the state. The state
approved it because less than 3% of Concord's housing is
classed as affordable.
   Concord policeman D.A. Goranson, who grew up in town,
favors the projects. "I know Walden Pond, and this isn't the
Walden Pond I knew as a child," he says. Anyway, he adds, the
area needs affordable housing. "Many town employees can't
live here because they can't afford it," he notes.
   Had it not been for Mr. Henley, the matter probably would
have been merely debated over coffee, talked about after
church. But then he stepped in. Radio stations began
promoting the concerts and the issue became more public.
   Mr. Henley and the Thoreauvians now promise to help find
another spot in Concord for affordable housing -- and pitch
in money to buy the land. But that will be easier said than
done. Notes Ms. Cutler, "Nobody supports affordable housing
unless it's someplace else. It's not easy to find another
site."
   If no other site can be found, Mr. Henley wrote that he
would "explore the possibility" of building the affordable
units at the existing site, but not the higher-priced condos.
Mr. Henley is no longer giving interviews.
   But first his group will have to raise the money to buy
that site and the office site, a total that could exceed $10
million. The two concerts this week might net $500,000,
supporters estimate, so more celebrity bashes may be
necessary.
   The Thoreauvians do have one well-heeled convert already:
Mr. Zuckerman. While insisting there is nothing wrong with
his proposed office building, he says he would happily sell
it for no profit -- and will even contribute $100,000 to
their cause.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
