</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   PAC Contributions to Senators Totaled
   $96.3 Million in '83-'88, Group Says
   ----
   By Jill Abramson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A20
</SO>
<IN>
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- U.S. senators collectively received $96.3
million in campaign contributions from political action
committees sponsored by corporations and labor unions in a
recent six-year period, according to a study by Common Cause.
   The study, released the same week the Senate is expected
to begin debating ways to overhaul the campaign-finance
system, showed that 44 senators received more than $1 million
each from PACs during 1983-1988, the period studied by the
self-styled citizens lobby group.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Senate's leader in PAC contributions was Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen (D., Texas), chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, who received $2.5 million. Three other senators --
Pete Wilson (R., Calif.), Slade Gorton (R., Wash.) and Phil
Gramm (R., Texas) -- also received more than $2 million from
PACs.
   "Special-interest PACs have contributed tens of millions
of dollars to obtain special access and influence," said
Common Cause President Fred Wertheimer.
   Financial-services industry PACs, including those
sponsored by savings and loan associations, were the biggest
corporate contributors, giving senators more than $8.5
million. Banking Committee Chairman Donald Riegle (D., Mich),
the subject of an ethics inquiry because of large
contributions he received from savings and loan executive
Charles Keating, was the Senate's top recipient from such
PACs, with $344,133.
   The second highest recipient from financial industry PACs
was Sen. Alfonse D'Amato (R., N.Y.), who received $309,433.
Sen. D'Amato is the subject of a Senate ethics inquiry that
focuses in part on campaign contributions he received from
executives of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. Sen. Alan Cranston
(D., Calif.), also under investigation for his ties to Mr.
Keating, received $209,195 from financial-industry PACS and
ranked ninth among beneficiaries of such groups.
   PACs representing oil and gas companies, utilities and
other energy interests gave senators more than $7 million.
Sen. Gramm was the top recipient with $382,103. The Texas
Republican also led in PAC contributions from real estate and
construction industry PACs, which gave him $193,874 out of a
total of $4.8 million contributed to senators.
   Insurance industry PACs gave a total of $45.7 million.
Sen. Bentsen was their top recipient with $213,900. PACs
representing food, restaurant and liquor associations gave a
total of $4.5 million; Sen. Gorton led with $147,182. Medical
and health industry PACs gave nearly $4 million, with Sen.
Dave Durenberger (R., Minn.) the top recipient with $156,061.
Pro-Israel PACs contributed $4.9 million and gave their
largest contributions to Sen. Paul Simon (D., Ill.) who
received $297,786.
   PACs sponsored by labor unions gave more than $14 million
to senators. Their top beneficiary was Sen. Thomas Daschle
(D., S.D.), who received $510,999 from such PACs in the
six-year period.
   Under current law, Senate candidates may receive a
contribution of up to $5,000 from any PAC in a primary
election and the same amount in a general election. There is
no overall ceiling on the amount of money a candidate can
receive from various PACs.
   Proposals to limit the role played by PACS are among the
most contentious items in the highly partisan fight over
campaign-finance. With seven senators facing pending ethics
inquiries, the Senate is under intense pressure to reduce the
role of special-interest money in politics, but lawmakers are
split over how to do so.
   Historically, Democrats have enjoyed higher levels of PAC
support and have been less cordial to proposals to limit
them. However, a bill introduced last month by Sen. David
Boren (D., Okla.) would place an aggregate ceiling on the
amount of PAC money a Senate candidate can receive. President
Bush has proposed changes that would, in effect, abolish
corporate and labor PACs, while other Republicans advocate
lowering the contribution limits from $5,000 to $1,000.
   Steven Stockmeyer, who represents a coalition of business
PACs, opposes all such proposals. "PACS are as diverse as
America is," he says. "To artificially limit them limits that
diversity."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900424-0087
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900424-0087.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Monday's Markets:
   Stocks Fall,
   Bonds Drop
   Moderately
   ---
   Worry About Rates
   Hurts Shares; Dollar
   Surges Against Mark
   ----
   By Douglas R. Sease
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   Interest rate fears continued to batter stock prices,
though bond prices declined only modestly.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 29.28 points to
2666.67 in light trading. Long-term bond prices lost about a
quarter of a point, or about $2.50 for each $1,000 of face
amount. Though small, the decline was the seventh consecutive
drop. The dollar rose sharply against the West German mark,
but much less markedly against the Japanese yen.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Analysts said the decline in stocks was a continuation of
the inflation and interest rate worries that pushed the Dow
Jones Industrial Average down nearly 56 points last week to
its lowest level in more than a month.
   Last week's market activity was led by the bond market,
where investors bid prices down sharply. As bond prices fell,
the interest rates on those securities rose, posing a threat
to already sluggish economic growth and giving investors an
attractive alternative to stocks. Although the bond price
decline moderated considerably yesterday, analysts said the
likelihood of further rate increases, including the
possibility that the Federal Reserve might soon push
short-term rates higher, continued to frighten investors away
from stocks.
   There also are worries that Japanese investors will be
assuming a much lower profile in the U.S. bond market in
coming months, a development that also could drive interest
rates higher. James Solloway, chief economist at Argus
Research in New York, noted that while Japanese investors
aren't the largest block of bondholders in the market, they
are influential. And with interest rates in Japan approaching
7.25%, the real returns available to them in Japan are about
as good as they are here without the currency risk of
investing in dollar-denominated securities.
   Mr. Solloway, contending stocks already are overvalued at
current interest rates, said there is likely to be a
psychological reaction among investors if the yield on the
Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond rises to 9%. The yield is
at 8.96%.
   "It's very difficult for stocks to beat a 9% yield on a
long-term basis," said Mr. Solloway. He suggests that stock
prices could tumble 10% to 15% if interest rates rise much
further.
   The dollar's rise against the West German mark followed
published reports that German monetary union will include a
one-to-one exchange rate for the bulk of East German savings
as well as wages and pensions. Currency traders said a broad
one-to-one exchange rate between the two Germanies'
currencies would be inflationary. The West German Bundesbank
has said it opposes a one-to-one exchange rate and central
bank officials have threatened to drive interest rates higher
if such an exchange rate is approved.
   In major market action:
                                                                                                       

   Stock prices sank in light trading. Volume on the New York
Stock Exchange totaled 136.2 million shares. Declining issues
on the Big Board were ahead of gainers 1229 to 328.
                                                                                                       

   Bond prices eased. The yield on the Treasury's benchmark
issue rose to 8.96%.
                                                                                                       

   The dollar strengthened against most major currencies. In
late New York trading the dollar was quoted at 1.6996 marks
and 157.60 yen compared with 1.6995 marks and 157.45 yen
Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900424-0086
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900424-0086.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Jefferies Is Hoping
   `Junk' Staffers Start
   California Dreamin'
   ---
   Move by New Yorkers Urged
   As Beverly Hills Group
   Of Drexel Comes Abroad
   ----
   By Michael Siconolfi
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   JEFG
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Jefferies Group Inc., after hiring a flock of
Drexel Burnham Lambert Group Inc.'s junk-bond traders in
California, is urging the rest of its "junk" staff here to
move to the city that made Drexel famous: Beverly Hills.
   The Los Angeles brokerage firm is quietly urging its
junk-bond professionals to leave New York for the California
city, where a junk-bond universe was built by Drexel's former
junk-bond chief Michael Milken.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The move will help ensure that the former Drexel traders
will feel at home and more easily retain their clients,
traders said. That's especially important at a time when the
junk market has contracted sharply and Drexel's junk
professionals are filtering throughout Wall Street and
elsewhere.
   Jefferies officials, for their part, sought to play down
the shift. "We have an open speaker system" throughout
Jefferies offices nationwide, says Frank Baxter, chief
executive officer. "Where someone is located isn't really
that important." Jefferies's equity operations in New York
won't be affected by the shift.
   Although some of Jefferies's junk-bond professionals "are
mutually considering whether they'd like to move West," Mr.
Baxter adds, he says there are no "present plans" to purge
their entire New York-based junk operations.
   The shift began several weeks ago, when Jefferies hired
seven former Drexel junk professionals -- nearly doubling the
size of its junk-bond staff, previously centered in New York,
in one fell swoop. As part of a negotiated deal, some traders
said, Jefferies promised the former Drexel executives that
they could stay in California.
   Since then, the firm's junk-bond professionals have been
reporting to David Sydorick, one of the former Drexel
salesmen who is based in Beverly Hills. And Ronald Davis,
former head of the firm's New York junk-bond group, already
has moved to the firm's Dallas office.
   Jefferies isn't the first brokerage firm to urge some of
its junk-bond staff to look West. Last year, Merrill Lynch &amp;
Co. had sought new offices for its growing junk operations in
Beverly Hills but has since decided to keep its junk-bond
trading desk in New York. Jefferies says it plans to
eventually shift its staff to the Westwood section of Los
Angeles.
   Meantime, a former Drexel junk-bond trader who lives in
California and recently moved to Jefferies concedes, "There's
no good business reason to be in California and not be part
of the Wall Street community." But, he adds, the former
Drexel employees all live in California and will easily fit
in at Jefferies.
   Besides, he says, "All we need is a telephone."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900424-0085
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900424-0085.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:
   Public Non-Financing
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   The closest thing this country has to a national
referendum is a box on everyone's 1040 IRS form. Since 1973
filers have been asked if they wanted $1 of their taxes to go
to a presidential-election fund. Though they are explicitly
told that checking "yes" won't raise their taxes, the number
of people who want to subsidize White House aspirants is
obviously diminishing. It fell from 29% in 1980 to 20% last
year. Despite this overwhelming rejection, Washington is
overflowing with proposals at the moment to extend public
financing to Congress. Not surprisingly, no one is even
suggesting that the money be raised by giving taxpayers a
"vote" on the matter with a checkoff system for congressional
elections. The results would likely be embarrassing.
</LP>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900424-0084
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900424-0084.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Who's News:
   Bank of New England Names McNamar,
   Ex-Treasury Aide, to Be Vice Chairman
   ----
   By Christopher J. Chipello
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   NEB WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   BOSTON -- Bank of New England Corp. named R.T. McNamar, a
former U.S. deputy Treasury secretary, as vice chairman.
   Mr. McNamar, 51 years old, will be responsible for
regulatory compliance, investor relations and corporate
communications at the financially troubled bank holding
company. The vice chairman's post had been vacant since the
end of January, when Richard Driscoll was forced to retire.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. McNamar will play a sensitive role. Bank of New
England is under strict orders from federal regulators to
improve its financial condition and its operations. And the
company's securities holders are watching anxiously to see
whether it can work its way out from under its massive loan
problems without government assistance. Any financial aid
from the government would probably wipe out any remaining
value in the company's shares and could mean big losses for
debt holders, as well.
   Mr. McNamar said in an interview that he sees "a
reasonable possibility that we can avoid" government
assistance. But he said it "will take another quarter or two"
of monitoring the Bank of New England loan portfolio before
the question of the company's viability can be answered with
greater assurance. Mr. McNamar said that he is "very
impressed" with the new loan-review process at Bank of New
England, but that the system will have to be checked against
factors such as rates of recovery on foreclosed real estate.
   First-quarter results are to be posted in the next couple
of weeks, and Lawrence Fish, the company's new chairman, has
warned that nonperforming assets will rise from the $2.3
billion reported as of Dec. 31, partly resulting from
deterioration in the New England real estate market and
partly reflecting the revised loan-review process.
Nonperforming assets include foreclosed loans and loans for
which payments are past due or considered to become
delinquent. Mr. Fish last week outlined a strategy to return
the company to profitability, and said the bank will seek to
place some of its problem assets in a separate entity --
often known as a "bad bank."
   Mr. McNamar and Mr. Fish became acquainted after Mr. Fish
left Bank of Boston Corp. in 1988 to become president and
chief operating officer of Columbia Savings &amp; Loan
Association in Beverly Hills, Calif. The two men met at the
suggestion of an executive recruiter they both knew in San
Francisco, and have kept in touch since, Mr. McNamar said.
   Mr. McNamar held the No. 2 job at the Treasury Department
from 1981 to 1985, and was responsible for domestic and
international capital markets, banking and tax policy. He was
in charge of the department's handling of the Third World
debt problem and served as principal negotiator for some
assistance packages from 1982 to 1984.
   Since leaving the government, he has run Conover &amp;
McNamar, a Los Angeles-based consulting and merchant banking
firm that did work for the World Bank and several private
banking companies. Co-founder C. Todd Conover, formerly U.S.
comptroller of the currency, has since left the firm. Mr.
McNamar, who started work at Bank of New England yesterday,
said Conover &amp; McNamar will be closed.
   Mr. McNamar, who joins the boards of Bank of New England
Corp. and its main banking affiliates in Massachusetts and
Connecticut, will have a personal financial stake in the
company's efforts to turn itself around: His compensation
package at Bank of New England, like Mr. Fish's, includes a
heavy weighting of stock options.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Bank of New England shares closed at $3.625, unchanged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
