<HL>
   Big Investors' Commission Rates May Have Hit a Low
   ----
   By James A. White
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Commission rates paid by large investors on
stock trades, which have been falling for more than a decade,
may have finally hit a low point.
   While skeptics dismiss it as no more than wishful thinking
by brokers, indications that institutional commission rates
have firmed -- and may even increase -- have surfaced in a
new study by Greenwich Associates, Greenwich, Conn.,
consultants who do exhaustive research on the investment
industry.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Greenwich's latest survey of 600 institutional investors
found that the 115 largest, each of which pays $5 million or
more in annual commissions, expect their pershare costs to
rise this year. Though the expected climb is tiny -- to an
average of 6.6 cents a share from 6.5 cents in 1989 -- it
marks the first time since 1980 that Greenwich turned up
evidence that large institutional commissions are on the
rise. Greenwich has been conducting the study for 17 years.
   "One-tenth of a cent does not a trend make, but it is the
first time that it hasn't gone south" in a decade, Greenwich
consultant James A. Bennett Jr. said of the institutional
rate. But the aggregate forecast from all 600 institutional
investors surveyed showed that commissions are expected to
slip to 8.7 cents a share from 8.9 cents this year.
   Even if commission rates for big investors have hit bottom
at about 6.6 cents a share, they are still too low for
brokers to make a profit trading stocks for customers, said
Kevin L. Risen, brokerage analyst at Banc One Asset
Management Corp. "Eight to 10 cents a share is what I
consider to be a level they can make a profit at," he said.
   And stock trading executives see little inclination by any
of their customers to allow rates to move up quickly.
   Robert M. Dewey Jr., managing director, equity trading and
sales, at Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp., said
that while institutions are talking about paying a bit more,
few are taking action. "You could put on one hand all the
people that have stepped up to the plate and said, `I want to
take my seven-cent commission up to eight cents,'" he said.
   With Wall Street's trading capacity still far larger than
necessary to handle the available business, many brokerage
executives remain doubtful that the slide in institutional
commission rates is over.
   "From what we have seen in the first quarter, there is no
indication that commissions are going up," said Stanley S.
Abel, chairman of Abel/Noser Corp., which specializes in
measuring stock trading costs. Brokers, he said, are "trying
to talk rates up," but customers still hold the upper hand.
   Ever since brokerage firms were forced to end their system
of fixed stock-commission rates in 1975, per-share trading
costs paid by big investors have declined steadily, squeezing
Wall Street's stock trading profits. And according to a big
securities firm, which declined to be identified, commission
rates kept tumbling in the first quarter of this year. An
executive at this firm said that from 1988 to 1989, average
commissions paid to the firm fell 4.79% to 6.56 cents a
share. For the first quarter of this year, commissions fell
another 2% to 6.42 cents a share, the lowest in this firm's
history.
   Some big investment firms are paying even less.
Independence Investment Associates, a money-management arm of
John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co., is typical of the big
investors that have significantly lowered their trading
costs. Independence's per-share commissions have fallen an
average of 10% annually in the past 15 years to 5.3 cents in
1989 from 25.6 cents in 1974.
   Still, some institutional investors said they are worried
that the drop in rates has gotten to the point that they are
paying hidden costs through the pricing and timing of their
stock trades.
   "We're starting to get a little concerned that we've
pushed these {commission} costs so low that maybe it is
affecting prices," said William F. Quinn, president of AMR
Investment Services Inc., which manages $6 billion for
employees of AMR Corp.'s American Airlines and other clients.
"We're hearing from a broad base of {money} managers that
liquidity isn't what it used to be," he said.
   As a result, Mr. Quinn said, he has authorized his outside
money managers to pay higher commissions if necessary, which
has resulted in AMR's per-share rate rising by perhaps half a
penny above its previous five-cents-a-share cost. "We've said
to managers that if they need to pay a little more
{commission} to get a trade done at the best price, they
should do it," he said.
   Joseph W. Perrone, chief investment officer of the $24
billion Texas Teacher Retirement System, also believes big
investors may have pushed Wall Street as hard as they can.
For the Texas teachers fund, with $9.5 billion in stocks,
saving a penny on the fund's average commission cost of six
to seven cents a share could easily get lost "in the noise
level," Mr. Perrone said. "While I'm sitting there
negotiating for one cent a share, I could lose $100,000 in
the market."
   "You've got to let those guys make some money or they
can't stay in business," he said. "We can just tell the
brokers not to write any commissions and they will just mark
up the stock."
   Mr. Dewey of Donaldson Lufkin said that despite customers'
haggling over ordinary business, large blocks that require
his firm to put up money to facilitate the trade are
commanding higher commissions. "When it comes to using our
capital to do a trade -- almost everybody is willing to pay
for that," he said.
   But some investors still believe the cost of trading is
too high in many cases. "I don't think it's low enough for
large traders," said Greta Marshall, former chief investment
officer of the $56 billion California Public Employees
Retirement System and now a money manager heading her own
firm.
   While she was at the California pension fund, Ms. Marshall
helped halve its average commission rate to five cents a
share, cutting off brokers who refused to adjust their fees.
But she noted that a nickel-a-share commission still amounts
to $500 on a 10,000-share trade. "It just doesn't cost that
much for a {trade} ticket," she said.
   Brokers, Ms. Marshall said, should boost charges to very
active traders, such as hedge funds, and cut them for those
who are usually in less of a hurry to get trades done, such
as pension funds.
   "The Street says, `We're not making any money,'" Ms.
Marshall said. "I say, `Maybe that's because you're
inefficient and you're not making people pay for things that
they use.'"
   ---
   Craig Torres contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900424-0049
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900424-0049.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Exxon Net Fell
   29% as Amoco's
   Profit Rose 1.7%
   ---
   Higher Crude Prices Boost
   Results for Production,
   Hurt Refining Margins
   ----
   By Allanna Sullivan and Caleb Solomon
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   XON AN ASH AHC
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
OIL, INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)
EARNINGS (ERN)
OIL, SECONDARY (OIS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Sharply higher crude oil prices boosted exploration and
production results at both Exxon Corp. and Amoco Corp., but
those same higher prices cut into chemical and refining
margins.
   Exxon operating profit in the first quarter rose slightly
although one-time items caused its net income to decline 29%.
Amoco profit rose 1.7%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Amoco said it paid an average of $20.79 a barrel for oil
in the quarter, more than $3 higher than a year ago. Because
crude oil is a raw material for so-called downstream
operations, chemical earnings were off sharply for both
companies, and gasoline refining and marketing profits were
weaker. Exxon and Amoco are the first major oil companies to
report first-quarter results, and other companies' earnings
are expected to follow the same pattern.
   Analysts say Exxon turned in a better first-quarter
performance than anticipated with its foreign exploration and
production business making a particularly strong showing.
Results "were better than what we were looking for," said
Frederick Leuffer, analyst for C.J. Lawrence Inc. Still,
Exxon lost 62.5 cents in composite trading yesterday on the
New York Stock Exchange to close at $45.75 a share.
   Exxon reported net income of $1.28 billion, or $1.01 a
share, compared with $1.81 billion, or $1.41 a share, during
the same period last year. But the year-earlier quarterly
profit included a $535 million gain related to an accounting
change. Revenue grew by 20% to $26.7 billion.
   Profitability was marred somewhat by the U.S. refining and
marketing business, which reported a loss of $28 million down
from earnings of $37 million. Exxon explained some of this by
saying that results in the U.S. were unfavorably affected by
the partial loss of operating capacity at the Baton Rouge
refinery following a major explosion and fire last December.
   Missing in the quarter's results were any additional
charges related to cleaning up the spill caused when one of
Exxon's tankers rammed an underwater reef and dumped almost
11 million gallons into Prince William Sound last year. Last
year Exxon took $1.38 billion in charges stemming from
cleanup of its giant Alaskan oil spill.
   Exxon made no reference in its current earnings report to
the oil spill, which has made it the pariah of the industry.
But analysts say they don't expect the company to take any
additional charges related to cleanup efforts, which are to
resume in Alaska on May 1. "I think Exxon has probably
overreserved" for the upcoming cleanup effort, said Bryan
Jacoboski, analyst for PaineWebber Group Inc.
   In the first quarter, Exxon, New York, purchased 2.2
million shares of its own stock at a cost of $104 million.
Analysts noted that the buy-back rate has slowed to its
lowest level in more than seven years. They speculated that
some of the money typically used for stock repurchases was
shifted into capital spending, which grew by 5% excluding the
$3.9 billion acquisition of Texaco Canada. The growth in
spending, albeit small, indicates "a more aggressive,
healthier approach" for the company, Mr. Jacoboski said.
   Amoco said net rose to $466 million, or 91 cents a share,
from $458 million, or 89 cents a share. The 1989 first
quarter included a special charge of $57 million for
consolidation activities. Revenue rose 9% to $7.13 billion
from $6.52 billion.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Amoco fell 75
cents to $50.25 a share.
   Like Exxon, Amoco's exploration and production earnings
surged, to $295 million from $203 million. Despite higher
natural gas prices in the quarter, Amoco reduced its natural
gas production, as did many producers when the price fell
sharply after the unusually bitter cold ended by February.
   Chicago-based Amoco said its chemical earnings fell 49% to
$80 million. The company said margins were lower, as they
have been for a number of quarters. A combination of higher
prices for crude -- the feedstock for petrochemicals -- with
lower chemical prices is behind the profit decline.
   With gasoline refining and marketing profit of $111
million in the quarter, results were down just slightly from
$114 million.
   Separately, Ashland Oil Inc., Ashland, Ky., by and large a
gasoline refiner and marketer without its own crude oil
production, had a weak quarter. It had net of $913,000, or
two cents a share, compared with a loss of $13.8 million, or
25 cents a share, which included a $9 million charge. Sales
rose to $1.97 billion from $1.78 billion.
   Amerada Hess Corp., New York, said net fell to $39.7
million, or 49 cents a share, from $220.2 milllion, or $2.70
a share. Amerada Hess earnings fell so sharply in part
because of its accounting method, which analysts say cuts
into reported earnings when crude prices fall during a
quarter, as they did in the first period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900424-0048
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900424-0048.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Howard Savings Bank:
   First-Period Loss Confirmed;
   Layoffs, Other Steps Slated
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   HWRD
</CO>
<LP>
   Driven to losses by the Northeast's real estate slump,
Howard Savings Bank, announced a plan to return to
profitability by cutting staff, raising service fees and
reducing nonperforming loans.
   At the Newark, N.J., bank's annual meeting, Leo J. Rogers
Jr., president, confirmed his projection last month of a
$17.5 million loss for the first quarter. The loss resulted
from the addition of $29.5 million to the bank's allowance
for possible loan losses during the quarter. In the
year-earlier quarter, Howard Savings Bank earned $8.5
million, or 59 cents a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Rogers said that about 10% of the current work force
of about 1,700 would be let go, with about 100 employees
offered early retirement at full pensions and other
reductions coming "through attrition." He said the bank's
first priority is to control and reduce nonperforming loans,
which will be supervised by the recently hired chief credit
officer, a new post.
   Mr. Rogers said Howard Savings will concentrate on
residential mortgages, home equity and other consumer loans
for the rest of the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900424-0047
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900424-0047.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Browning-Ferris Had
   Loss of $226.3 Million
   In Fiscal 2nd Period
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C22
</SO>
<CO>
   BFI
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<LP>
   HOUSTON -- Browning-Ferris Industries Inc. reported a loss
of $226.3 million, or $1.48 a share, for its second quarter
ended March 31, reflecting a previously announced charge to
exit the hazardous-waste business.
   Earlier this month, the waste management concern disclosed
the $295 million charge. The firm has been buffeted by low
margins and regulatory problems in its hazardous-waste
business and plans to focus on solid waste, recycling and
medical-waste disposal.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Revenue was $708.5 million. In the year-ago second
quarter, Browning had net income of $58.8 million, or 39
cents a share, on restated revenue of $582.3 million.
   Results for the year-ago period were restated to reflect
the discontinued hazardous-waste operation.
   In the six months, Browning-Ferris had a loss of $159.8
million, or $1.05 a share, compared with net of $118.4
million, or 79 cents a share. Revenue increased to $1.41
billion from a restated $1.15 billion.
