<HL>
   Who's News:
   Guinness Names Kettle
   President and Chief
   Of Schenley Industries
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS U.GUI
</CO>
<LP>
   STAMFORD, Conn. -- Guinness PLC named Graham Kettle
president and chief executive officer of Schenley Industries
Inc., a Dallas distilling and distributing subsidiary of the
United Distillers unit of Guinness.
   The 42-year-old Mr. Kettle currently is managing director
of Arthur Bell Distillers, which oversees sales and marketing
for United Distillers in the United Kingdom.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In his new posts, he succeeds James Espey, who has been
acting president and chief executive officer since Alexander
Berk, 40, resigned in March to pursue other business
interests.
   Mr. Espey, 47, becomes chairman of Schenley, while
continuing as regional managing director of United's North
American operations here. Joseph Heid, 43, was named vice
chairman of Schenley; he will continue as chief financial
officer of United Distillers America.
   United, like its parent Guinness, is based in London.
Guinness has brewing and distilling interests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900424-0023
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900424-0023.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   BONN PROPOSED a generous plan for monetary union with East
Germany.
   In a bid to calm East German fears, the West German
government unveiled the outlines of a plan for merging the
two nations' currencies. Under the proposal, individual East
German wages and savings of as much as $2,373 would be
changed into West German marks at a favorable one-to-one
rate. The offer is considered a major concession to East
Berlin, which argued that workers need to be cushioned during
a transition to a market economy.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   East Germany said it would give more than $4 million to
aid survivors of the World War II Holocaust, in which the
Nazis killed six million Jews.
   ---
   THE U.S. IS PRESSING its efforts to win freedom for all
hostages in the Mideast.
   While reiterating its refusal to make any deals, the White
House said it was continuing "to probe all sources of
information" about seven missing Americans, and Bush renewed
his call for their "unconditional" release. In West Germany,
Polhill, who was freed Sunday by pro-Iranian extremists,
underwent a physical examinaton and doctors said he was
malnourished and mildly dehydrated. The 55-year-old New
Yorker had been held for more than three years.
   The foreign minister of Iran, which joined Syria in
helping arrange Polhill's release, reportedly called for
Israel to free a Shiite cleric abducted in July.
   ---
   NEPAL'S POLICE BATTLED mobs, threatening a transition to
democracy.
   In the first major violence since the Himalayan kingdom
lifted a ban on political parties two weeks ago, police
opened fire on demonstrators after crowds rampaged in
Katmandu. At least 11 people were reported killed, including
six police officers beaten to death by protesters. The mobs
accused security forces of condoning a monarchist group
blamed for a wave of crime aimed at undermining Nepal's
four-day-old government. A curfew was imposed on the capital.
   Prime Minister K.P. Bhattarai, who has said Nepal may be
headed for a constitutional monarchy, met with King Birendra
to review the situation.
   ---
   Lithuania closed the Baltic republic's only oil refinery
because of the Kremlin's cutoff of energy supplies. The prime
minister said the republic, which last month declared its
independence from Moscow, may try to sell gold to import
fuel, and the president said Gorbachev should renounce the
use of Soviet troops in Lithuania.
                                                                                                       

   Bush plans to meet today with congressional leaders to
discuss a U.S. response to the Soviet Union's standoff with
Lithuania. The White House also welcomed what it called signs
of flexibility from Moscow, which said Soviet leaders were
willing to open talks with the republic if it froze for two
years its move toward secession.
   ---
   The Supreme Court rejected an appeal by an Oregon woman
who doesn't want to share parental rights with a California
man who donated his sperm for artificial insemination. The
justices refused to block a trial in which the man would seek
to prove he acted only after the woman said she would let him
help raise the child, a girl born in 1986.
   ---
   NASA prepared for today's scheduled liftoff of the space
shuttle Discovery, the second attempt at launching the
spacecraft, which is to place the Hubble Space Telescope into
orbit. The space agency said the mechanical problems that
grounded the shuttle April 10 have been repaired, and
forecasters predicted favorable weather.
   ---
   China's Premier Li arrived in the Soviet Union and met
with Premier Ryzhkov, who said the two nations would
cooperate on nuclear energy and space research. The trip by
Li, the first Chinese head of government to visit Moscow in
26 years, is aimed at promoting ties and easing border
tensions.
   ---
   Sudan's military leader said loyalist forces crushed a
rebellion by junior military officers in the African nation,
the second such attempt in a month against Khartoum's ruling
junta. Two retired army officers were accused of plotting the
revolt and arrested. No casualties were reported.
   ---
   A center-right coalition claimed victory in Sunday's
multiparty parliamentary elections in Yugoslavia's republic
of Croatia. In neighboring Slovenia, a progressive Communist
won a presidential runoff election.
   ---
   Post-Earth Day demonstrators blocked traffic and
overturned trash bins along Wall Street to protest corporate
involvement in pollution. About 200 people were arrested.
Trading began on schedule. At the Pacific Stock Exchange in
San Francisco, 49 people were arrested during a similar
protest.
   ---
   Died: Paulette Goddard, 84, Hollywood actress of the 1930s
and '40s who starred in her then-husband Charlie Chaplin's
"Modern Times," near Ascona, Switzerland.
</TEXT>
