900424-0003.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   ITC to Investigate
   Firm's Complaint
   On Chips From Korea
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   C.HEI F.THM IR
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)
INDUSTRIAL EQUIPMENT, MACHINE TOOLS (IND)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The U.S. International Trade Commission
agreed to investigate a complaint by SGS-Thomson
Microelectronics Inc. that its patents are being infringed by
imports of computer memory chips made by a South Korean
company.
   SGS-Thomson, based in Carrollton, Texas, said Hyundai
Electronics Industries Co. and its California-based
subsidiary, Hyundai Electronics America, infringed on its
patents. The U.S. company is asking the ITC to ban the
offending imports, which include several types of dynamic
random access memories, or DRAMs, and static random access
memories, or SRAMs.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   SGS-Thomson, which is jointly owned by Thomson SA of
France and Istituto per la Recostruzione Industriale of
Italy, is the successor to Mostek Corp., which registered the
U.S. patents at the center of the controversy in the 1970s
and 1980s.
   The complaint is the first trade action taken by any U.S.
semiconductor producer against imports from South Korea. The
U.S. industry has been apprehensive there would be a surge of
computer-chip imports from South Korea, which recently has
increased its semiconductor production capacity.
   SGS-Thomson also has filed a lawsuit in federal district
court in Texas against Hyundai. In the suit, filed Feb. 27,
SGS-Thomson is seeking money damages and a permanent
injunction to halt alleged patent infringements.
   Separately, acting on another trade complaint, the ITC
decided to investigate charges by Ingersoll-Rand Co., a New
Jersey maker of power-tools, that its U.S. trademarks
covering "air-impact" wrenches have been infringed by
manufacturers in Taiwan and by Astro Pneumatic Tool Co., Los
Angeles, which distributes the Taiwan-made wrenches in the
U.S.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900424-0002
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900424-0002.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   EECO Might Seek
   Chapter 11 if Lender
   Puts Pact in Default
</HL>
<DATE>
04/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EEC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   SANTA ANA, Calif. -- EECO Inc. said it might seek
bankruptcy-law protection from creditors if Sanwa Bank of
California declares the high-technology electronics products
maker's $10 million credit agreement in default.
   The accord expired March 31.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   EECO's stock didn't open for trading yesterday on the
American Stock Exchange because of the news. Friday, the
shares closed at $1.75, unchanged.
   Late yesterday, EECO said it had recommended that the
exchange suspend trading in its stock until "its financial
condition is clarified." The company said it didn't know when
that might be.
   EECO said that if Sanwa calls the loan, the company could
have trouble getting other funding because of its poor
financial condition. The company then would have to consider
other options, it said, "including a restructuring under the
protection of Chapter 11" of the federal Bankruptcy Code.
   Robert Bonney, EECO chairman and chief executive officer,
said in an interview that Sanwa has held off declaring the
agreement in default while the company pursued the sale of
some or all of its businesses. But he added that Sanwa "could
call the loan at any time."
   Sanwa declined to comment.
   EECO has said it expects to report a $10.3 million net
loss for 1989. Posting of its financial results had been
delayed by a proposed sale of its Maxi-Switch computer
keyboard unit. In 1988, EECO had a loss of $13.2 million, on
sales of $13.9 million.
   The company also said that negotiations with a potential
purchaser of Maxi-Switch had broken off. Terms of the
proposed sale, EECO said, weren't satisfactory to Sanwa,
which holds liens on the unit's assets. The company said it
is in preliminary discussions with two new possible buyers of
the unit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
